{{DEFAULTSORT:Erdos-Szekeres conjecture}}
[[Category:Conjectures]]

An '''ethnolect''' is a [[variety (linguistics)|variety]] of a [[language]] associated with a certain [[ethnic]] or [[culture|cultural]] subgroup. An ethnolect may be a distinguishing mark of social identity, both within the group and for outsiders. The term combines the concepts of an [[ethnic group]] and [[dialect]].
The term was first used to describe the monolingual [[English language|English]] of descendants of European immigrants in [[Buffalo, New York]].<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Carlock |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Wölck |first2=Wolfgang |chapter=A method for isolating diagnostic linguistic variables: The Buffalo ethnolects experiment |editor=David Sankoff and Henrietta Cedergren |title=Variation Omnibus |location=Edmonton |publisher=Linguistic Research |year=1981 |pages=17-24}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=This is a primary source; it does not show itself to be the first use.|date=July 2013}}
The idea of an ethnolect relates to linguistic variation and to ethnic identity. According to [[Joshua Fishman]], a [[sociology of language|sociologist of language]], the processes of [[standard language|language standardization]] and [[nationalism]] in modern societies make links between language and ethnicity salient to users.<ref name="Fishman">{{Cite book|last=Fishman|first=Joshua|chapter=Language and ethnicity: The view from within |title=The Handbook of Sociolinguistics |editor=Florian Coulmas |year=1997 |location=Oxford |publisher=Blackwell |pages=327-343}}</ref>
Ethnicity can affect linguistic variation in ways that reflect a social dimension of language usage. The way in which ethnic groups interact with one another shapes their usage of language. Dialects may be defined by [[phonology|phonological]], [[syntax|syntactic]], and [[lexicon|lexical]] variation. Such linguistic difference may be as important as social markers for a particular ethnic group.<ref name="Fishman" />
== Criticism of "Ethnolect" approach == Some twenty-first century linguists object to broader application of the term ''ethnolect'' to describe linguistic differences that are believed to reflect ethnic group affiliation. According to these scholars, this may inaccurately posit ethnicity as the central explanation for linguistic difference, when in fact there may be other variables which are more influential to an individual's speech.<ref name=":0">Becker, Kara. (2014). Linguistic repertoire and ethnic identity in New York City. Language and Communication 35: 43-54. </ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Eckert|first=Penelope|date=2008-03-01|title=Where do ethnolects stop?|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/13670069080120010301|journal=International Journal of Bilingualism|language=en|volume=12|issue=1-2|pages=25–42|doi=10.1177/13670069080120010301}}</ref><ref>Brubaker, Rogers, Mara Loveman, and Peter Stamatov (2004) Ethnicity as cognition. eory and Society 33(1): 31–64.</ref><ref>Benor, S. B. (2010), Ethnolinguistic repertoire: Shifting the analytic focus in language and ethnicity[http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1467-9841.2010.00440.x/full#en1 1]. Journal of Sociolinguistics, 14: 159–183. doi:10.1111/j.1467-9841.2010.00440.x</ref>
Some scholars also point out that the common use of ''ethnolect'' is used to compare the "ethnolects" of ethnic minorities with the "standard" speech of ethnic majorities, which is designated as the regional dialect instead of as a majority ethnolect.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />
==See also== * [[Accent (sociolinguistics)]] * [[Diglossia]] * [[Isogloss]] * [[Sociolect]] * [[Sociolinguistics]]
